\begin_layout Standard
In order to reduce uncertainties the number of samples used must be large
 (often several thousand).
 If one want to cover delayed neutron, large samples are required (at least
 100 seconds) and the simulated signal can required unacceptable CPU time
 or experiment duration.
 As a consequence, 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{\infty}$
\end_inset

 are in practice estimated throw formulas depending on 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{2}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y(\tau)$
\end_inset

, making these values dependent of both the samples width (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{2}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{\infty}(\tau)$
\end_inset

) and the underlying theory:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
R_{2}(\tau) & =\frac{1}{\omega(\tau)}\,Y_{2}(\tau)\label{eq:R2_omega}\\
Y_{\infty}(\tau) & =2\,\frac{R_{2}(\tau)}{R_{1}}\nonumber \\
\omega\,(\lambda,\tau) & =1-\frac{1-e^{-\lambda\tau}}{\lambda\tau}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

Wehre 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 is the inverse of the neutron lifetime which includes slowing-down time
 in the detector.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that for the NMC values to be meaningful and usable for other measures
 (calculation of total multiplication for instance), the experiment must
 be in a steady state, i.e.
 the power remains constant over time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Direct method
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 be the mean rate of source events (i.e.
 the mean number of histories per time unit) and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{N}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

the probability for an history to create 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 detections.
 Both values comes from simulation results.
 In particular, the association of each detection with the fission chain
 identifier makes it possible to calculate the 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{N}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

quantity.
 That being said, for a stationary process the mean rate of detections from
 histories creating 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 detections is 
\begin_inset Formula $S\cdot p_{N}\cdot C_{N}^{1}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 denotes the binomial coefficient.
 Summing over all possible numbers of detections gives the single rate of
 detections:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathring{Y}_{1}=S\sum_{N=1}^{\infty}p_{N}\cdot C_{N}^{1}\label{eq:y1_final}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this formula as well as for the following, the circle denotes values
 calculated using the 
\emph on
direct method
\emph default
.
 One may note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{Y}_{1}$
\end_inset

 does not depend on any samples width values and thus 
