\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
it is equal to its asymptotic value 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{R}_{1}$
\end_inset

.

\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 To be consistent with formulas presented in section 2 the expected number
 of detections per samples 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{m}_{1}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{Y}_{1}\,\tau$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The same approach is then applied for the double counting rate.
 Considering the mean rate of correlated pairs triggered by the 
\emph on
ith
\emph default
 detection of histories creating 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 detections is 
\begin_inset Formula $S\cdot p_{N}\cdot C_{N-i}^{1}$
\end_inset

, the mean double counting rate created by histories having 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 detections is equal to:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S\cdot p_{N}\sum_{i=1}^{N-1}C_{N-i}^{1}=S\cdot p_{N}\cdot C_{N}^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Taking into account all histories with any number of detections gives the
 asymptotic mean double counting rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{R}_{2}$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathring{R}_{2}=S\sum_{N=2}^{\infty}p_{N}\cdot C_{N}^{2}\label{eq:r2_final}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Contrary to the 
\emph on
analog method,
\emph default
 the 
\emph on
direct method 
\emph default
gives directly access to the asymptotic double counting rate without the
 need of intermediate formulas.
 As a consequence, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{R}_{2}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset

do not depends of neither 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 or an underlying theory but only on the number of simulated histories.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are now interested in the calculation of the non-asymptotic value of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{R}_{2}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{Y}_{2}(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 Let's consider a first detection in the time range 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[t_{1},t_{1}+dt_{1}\right]$
\end_inset

 and a second one inside 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[t_{2},t_{2}+dt_{2}\right]$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}<t_{2}$
\end_inset

, the average number of correlated pairs of detections 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{r}$
\end_inset

 between two correlated detections distant of 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}-t_{1}$
\end_inset

 is: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q_{r}(t_{2}-t_{1})\,dt_{1}\cdot dt_{2}=\mathring{R}_{2}\cdot pdf(t_{2}-t_{1})\,dt_{1}\cdot dt_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With 
\begin_inset Formula $pdf$
\end_inset

 the probability density function of the time intervals between any pair
 of detections of an history i.e.
 the auto-correlation function.
 Once again the fission chain identifier provided by the simulation code
 allows the direct calculation of the PDF.
 The average counts in the time ranges 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[t_{1},t_{1}+dt_{1}\right]$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[t_{2},t_{2}+dt_{2}\right]$
\end_inset

 that are uncorrelated pairs of detections is equal to the product of the
 average detection rate: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
Q_{a}(t_{2}-t_{1})\,dt_{1}\cdot dt_{2}=\mathring{R}_{1}{}^{2}\,dt_{1}\cdot dt_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Summing 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{r}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{a}$
\end_inset

 gives the well-known Rossi-Alpha distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}Q(t_{2}-t_{1})dt_{1}\cdot dt_{2} & =\left(Q_{a}(t_{2}-t_{1})+Q_{r}(t_{2}-t_{1})\right)dt_{1}\cdot dt_{2}\\
 & =\left(\mathring{R}_{1}^{\,\,2}+\mathring{R}_{2}\cdot pdf(t_{2}-t_{1})\right)dt_{1}\cdot dt_{2}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where the subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 refer to the words 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

accidental
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

real
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 as often used with the Rossi-Alpha method 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "NMC Ensslin"

\end_inset

.
 With 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Q_{r}$
\end_inset

 defined, one can now calculate 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{m}_{2a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{m}_{2r}$
\end_inset

 which respectively correspond to the expected number of uncorrelated or
 correlated pairs of detection in samples of width 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 This is achieved by summing for each detection occurring at 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{1}\leqslant\tau$
\end_inset

 the second detections occurring at 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{2}\leqslant\tau$
\end_inset

 :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\mathring{m}_{2r}(\tau) & =\int_{0}^{\tau}dt_{1}\cdot\int_{t_{1}}^{\tau}Q_{r}(t_{2}-t_{1})\cdot dt_{2}\\
 & =\mathring{R}_{2}\int_{0}^{\tau}cdf(t)\cdot dt
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:m2r}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\mathring{m}_{2a}(\tau) & =\int_{0}^{\tau}dt_{1}\cdot\int_{t_{1}}^{\tau}Q_{a}(t_{2}-t_{1})\cdot dt_{2}\\
 & =\frac{1}{2}\mathring{R}_{1}^{\,\,2}\,\tau^{2}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
With 
\begin_inset Formula $cdf$
\end_inset

 the cumulative density function of the time intervals between any pair
 of detections of an history.
 Combination of the previous equations gives the final expression of the
 doubles counting rate as calculated with the 
\emph on
direct method 
\emph default
:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{aligned}\mathring{Y}_{2}(\tau) & =\frac{\mathring{m}_{2r}(\tau)}{\tau}\\
 & =\frac{\mathring{R}_{2}}{\tau}\,\intop_{0}^{\tau}dt\cdot cdf(t)
\end{aligned}
\label{eq:y2_final}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that the definition of the Feynman-Y values as two times the ratio
 between the double and simple counting rate remains valid so that no specific
 derivation is required:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathring{Y}=2\,\frac{\mathring{R}_{2}}{\mathring{R}_{1}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathring{Y_{\infty}}(\tau)=2\,\frac{Y_{2}(\tau)}{Y_{1}}\label{eq:y_final}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Back to Eq.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:m2r"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\int_{0}^{\tau}cdf(t)\cdot dt$
\end_inset

 behaves asymptotically like 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $cdf(\tau)$
\end_inset

 approaches unity.
 Let us now define a function 
\begin_inset Formula $w(\tau)$
\end_inset

 that approaches unity as 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

 tends towards infinity, and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 the number of pairs of detections in a gate of width 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau$
\end_inset

.
 As 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2}$
\end_inset

 contains both correlated and uncorrelated pairs of detections, 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2r}(\tau)$
\end_inset

, can also be written as the following :
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}m_{2r}(\tau) & =m_{2}(\tau)-m_{2a}(\tau)\\
 & =m_{2}(\tau)-\frac{1}{2}m_{1}^{\,\,2}
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is now possible to express the asymptotic doubles counting rate
\begin_inset space ~
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\mathring{R}_{2}(\tau)$
\end_inset

 as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $w(\tau)$
\end_inset

.
 The deduced equation is similar to the one obtained in Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:R2_omega"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathring{R}_{2}(\tau)=\frac{\mathring{Y}_{2}(\tau)}{w(\tau)}=\frac{m_{2}(\tau)-\frac{1}{2}m_{1}^{2}}{\tau\cdot w(\tau)}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The above reasoning does not differentiate between sources.
 For instance, if histories are created by both spontaneous fissions and
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\alpha-n\right)$
\end_inset

 reactions, 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 combines these two types of sources.
 However, for practical reasons it is sometimes interesting to differentiate
 sources in simulations: one may perform a set of simulations with only
 spontaneous fission sources and another set of simulations with only 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\alpha-n\right)$
\end_inset

