\begin_layout Section
Conclusion and future work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Traditionally, NMC values are calculated using similar tools to exploit
 the detections obtained by the experiment's detectors or by simulation.
 However, in some cases this approach can be very CPU intensive.
 The 
\emph on
direct method
\emph default
 uses additional information provided by the simulations to significantly
 reduce uncertainties and thus simulation times.
 However, as the present situation stands, this method cannot completely
 replace the traditional method.
 The main identified limitations are the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
requirement of sub-critical system in a steady state (i.e.
 constant power with time);
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
detector dead time not take into account;
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
higher order of counting rates (triple, etc.) are not yet derive.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Concerning the last point, it should be noted that these values are often
 difficult to obtain by simulation due to the need of a high detection efficienc
y to keep the variance reasonable.
 Therefore the development of the calculation of this value with the 
\emph on
direct method
\emph default
 could be very advantageous for applications that use these types of measures.
\end_layout

